title_sort: louisa van velsor whitman to walt whitman, [11–13 february 1873]
title: Louisa Van Velsor Whitman to Walt Whitman, [11–13 February 1873]
text: well my dear waltWalthow are you this morning i would very much like to come in and see you and get your breakfast for you but as i cantcan't i must content myself with writing these few lines we have had later news from poor dear mattyMatty jeffJeffie wrote the 7th she was more comfortable and her spells of coughfingcoughing was somewhat esiereasier i think we shall get a letter to day from Jeffy if i doodo i will write to you again walterWalter dear i got your letter yesterdyesterday i am glad to you are gaining some if but slowly if we had a home waltWalt you might loaf as long you wanted to but i gessguess you will be glad to get out in the open air once more i shouldentshouldn't wonder if staying in the house so much made your head worse its bad enough to have any thing the matter with the head its bad enoughfenough to be disabled any where but we cantcan't run away from sickness so we have to be thankfullthankful its no worsworse i have felt very sad walterWalter dear thinking of dear mattyMatty Jeffy writes she wants to see you and me poor poor matt good bie dear waltWalt keep up your spirits and hope for the best what a good fellow petePete isi have had quite a lot of correspondence from new yorkNew York concerning your condition our relations Louisa Van Velsor Whitman to Walt Whitman, [11–13 February 1873]
